WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.920
All right. Well, thank you. You know, as mentioned, I'm here to talk about what are we counting.

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:10.080
I had to do it, where I posit, had to do a little pun.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:16.760
So, at some point in your open source journey, someone is going to come to you with a question.

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:21.920
Might be a vice president. It might be a CEO. It might be some other stakeholder. They're

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:27.760
going to come and ask you a question. And that question is really, really, really simple.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:36.080
They're going to say, hey, how is open source adoption going? It's a really simple question.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:43.000
But it is incredibly difficult to answer. And when I see questions like this, one thing

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.119
pops in my head. And that is Tom Hanks in the movie Apollo 13 with his famous line,

00:00:50.119 --> 00:00:58.439
Houston, we have a problem. Now, you might be thinking, Ben, why are you here? Why are

00:00:58.439 --> 00:01:03.720
you here asking, telling us about this question? And also you might be asking, Ben, why are

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:10.279
you wearing Beetlejuice looking pants? The second one, I just like them. The first question,

00:01:10.279 --> 00:01:17.839
it's because I lead open source adoption at GSK R&D. This question happened to me. A VP

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:23.279
came and asked me and said, hey, how is open source adoption going? And similar to the

00:01:23.279 --> 00:01:28.199
hypothetical I just gave you, Houston, we have a problem flashed in front of my eyes

00:01:28.199 --> 00:01:34.279
as I tried to fumble around with holistic measures and things like that about, hey,

00:01:34.279 --> 00:01:39.919
how is open source adoption going? So before I tell you how we actually solve that problem,

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:45.040
how we answer that question, you need to know a couple of things. First, what does a bio

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:51.160
status organization do? We do two things. One, we write statistical tests to make sure

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:57.440
that our drugs are safe. And the second thing is we make we write statistical tests to determine

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:01.760
if our drugs are effective. That is at the core of our business. That is what we do.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:06.519
You should know that. The other question or the other thing that you need to know is why

00:02:06.519 --> 00:02:13.720
did our VP ask us this question? Well, we've been on a journey for a long time. Since 2020,

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:17.919
we've been putting all the pieces together for R adoption. We've been putting together

00:02:17.919 --> 00:02:22.679
the platform where we do our R work. We've been putting together the process. How do

00:02:22.679 --> 00:02:27.759
you do QC in R? We've been doing all the training. How do we move people from SAS to R? How do

00:02:27.759 --> 00:02:32.720
we actually build them up to be able to use R? We had to get the pipeline on board. It

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:37.199
sounds simple, but it's really hard to convince a clinical trial to move and adopt different

00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:41.960
tools or a different programming language. And then finally, the tools. We had to put

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:46.679
the tools in place and surround R and our different platforms and process to make people

00:02:46.679 --> 00:02:52.960
effective and efficient. If you're interested in sort of the in-depth of how we did this,

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:59.119
there's a link. You can search Posit GSK Enterprise Adoption on YouTube. We go into a really,

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:03.119
really in-depth conversation about this. I would check it out.

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:09.300
So we've been putting this these pieces in place since 2022 or 2020. And so as a result,

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:15.100
in August of 2023, we had two commitments from our leadership. First, all central tools

00:03:15.100 --> 00:03:21.460
had to be built using open source languages. And then the second is 50% of our code needs

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:26.300
to be written in an open source language by the end of 2025. It's the end of 2025, so

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:32.660
we're coming up on the deadline. So you have the context now. So how do we actually go

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:39.419
about answering our vice president's question? Again, similar to Apollo 13, we needed to

00:03:39.419 --> 00:03:45.419
figure out how to make a square peg fit into a round hole with using just the tools that

00:03:45.419 --> 00:03:50.440
we had in our organization. For those not familiar, Pharma is very highly regulated.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:55.059
And as a result, our tools are pretty limited about what we can introduce into our environments

00:03:55.059 --> 00:03:58.380
because we need to make sure, one, quality is good and we can trust all the different

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:05.740
outputs. So what was the tool that we had to pick? How did we go about doing this? Well,

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:16.899
the tool we ended up using is GitHub. But more specifically, the GitHub APIs. So one

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:21.100
of the tools that we introduced as part of our pieces was GitHub. And we said all studies

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:27.179
must use version control. That was our mandate. So that was how we kind of started to figure

00:04:27.179 --> 00:04:33.420
out answering this question. Now, if you've ever been on a GitHub repo page, there's tons

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:39.420
and tons and tons of information. The one I care most about is on the bottom right.

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:45.100
It's called language statistics. And what it does is it calculates in a repo how much

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:51.059
of a certain programming language is actually there in the default branch or the main branch.

00:04:51.059 --> 00:04:55.179
We care about that because that helps us to be able to say, all right, if all our clinical

00:04:55.179 --> 00:05:02.579
studies are in GitHub, can we then determine what is our adoption? So we started to play

00:05:02.579 --> 00:05:08.739
around with it and we said, great, we love this language statistics measure. Is there

00:05:08.739 --> 00:05:15.739
an API or are we going to have to web scrape every single GitHub repo page at GSK and pull

00:05:15.739 --> 00:05:23.260
this out the hard way? Luckily, there's an API endpoint. This will come back a little

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:28.420
bit later. But everything that you see on a GitHub page I'm just hitting on the browser

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:33.179
is literally accessible via an API endpoint. It's great. Thank you, GitHub. It makes our

00:05:33.179 --> 00:05:40.059
lives a lot easier. So we said, great. API endpoint exists. How do we actually access

00:05:40.059 --> 00:05:43.899
it? Are we going to have to write some custom scripts? Is there a package available? How

00:05:43.899 --> 00:05:49.260
do we actually go about doing this? Well, similar with the R community, hopefully you've

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:55.260
experienced it. Ask and you shall receive. And we actually realized the GH package which

00:05:55.260 --> 00:06:00.459
exists out there for a different use case can be used to write complex queries. You

00:06:00.459 --> 00:06:05.380
might have interacted with the GH package, set up your personal access tokens. It sits

00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:11.339
within uses, I believe. So it's a great way to, you know, get things started. But it's

00:06:11.339 --> 00:06:18.820
a great way to access the API. So you can actually write incredibly complex queries.

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:23.140
Like I said, it's usually used sort of on the easy stuff, but also can be used on the

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:31.140
hard stuff. It's kind of cool. So we figured that out. And then what did we start doing?

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:35.420
What you would expect. We started to explore and pull all that data through the API and

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:41.859
started to pull a lot of different information. It actually became overwhelming. What do you

00:06:41.859 --> 00:06:50.859
actually start to measure? So, do you count the number of outputs in this study? Do you

00:06:50.859 --> 00:06:55.619
count the number of production programs or key C programs using R? Do you count both?

00:06:55.619 --> 00:07:01.619
Is that double counting? Do you count the memory size of programs? Does that matter

00:07:01.619 --> 00:07:09.779
to you? Do you count the number of studies using R, no matter how much or how little?

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:16.700
Do you care about the growth of R versus other languages? Do you time box it? This is everything

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:20.540
that kind of went through our minds when we were going through all the GitHub API metrics

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:25.779
that were available to us. And we kind of really hit the analysis paralysis stage. Because

00:07:25.779 --> 00:07:31.100
really what's difficult is it's really hard to figure out what you need to measure to

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:37.019
satisfy that vice president's question, even though it is so simple. So we decided to sit

00:07:37.019 --> 00:07:44.019
back and think about it a little bit. And we channeled our inner Kevin Bacon, again

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:52.579
in Apollo 13, kept it nice and simple. Just decided to add, basically, and do some really

00:07:52.579 --> 00:07:59.579
simple summary statistics. These are the four things that are important to us. One, relative

00:08:00.859 --> 00:08:06.260
R size. We care about the R code size out of the total programming language. So for

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:11.899
our use case, a lot of R versus S. We care about the total number of repos with any usage

00:08:11.899 --> 00:08:17.899
of R. We care about repos where R code is above a target percentage. And we care about

00:08:17.899 --> 00:08:23.500
the growth of R. The reason why we care about the growth of R is we have huge legacy code

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:30.220
bases. But if we can see the growth of R versus other languages higher, that's good for us.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:35.140
Because that tells us that people are going to, at some point, be able to eclipse our

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:39.260
legacy. And that's what's really important when you start to compare, you know, relative

00:08:39.260 --> 00:08:45.659
R size. You have to add that context. Great. So we took our metrics and we put it in an

00:08:45.659 --> 00:08:52.020
incredibly fancy dashboard. And you'll get to see what it looks like. Well, sort of.

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:56.179
This is our dashboard, but obviously all the metrics removed. I can't show you those metrics.

00:08:56.179 --> 00:08:59.940
I'm sorry. But just imagine, you put some fancy metrics there and it looks really, really

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:06.820
cool. So we're able to do this as a one-off. How do you actually put this into production

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:12.380
so it's updated every single week? This is how we did it. It's a little confusing, or

00:09:12.380 --> 00:09:15.700
not confusing. There's a lot going on, so I'm going to walk you through it. But basically

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:22.700
we go GitHub, source, all the way to our analysis. And it's orchestrated by Posit. So first step.

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:30.700
One, we use the GH package to do an API query. We then take our raw data and dump it into

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:39.380
Azure Data Lake Storage. We do this once a week, you know, Sunday night, and it's all

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:44.979
automated and coordinated by Posit Connect. After that raw data storage job is done and

00:09:44.979 --> 00:09:49.219
completed, we then use some R scripts to do processing and transformation, adding in a

00:09:49.219 --> 00:09:53.900
little extra information from our internal systems. And then once that's done, we dump

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:58.900
it back into, again, Azure Data Lake Storage. You want a copy of raw and you want a copy

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:05.900
of transformed. Again, coordinated by Posit Connect. After that job is done, we then kick

00:10:06.299 --> 00:10:12.099
off a job to do data visualization, quarter dashboards and shiny dashboard deployment.

00:10:12.099 --> 00:10:17.460
So on Monday morning, if our VP cares, he or she can take a look at it and say, all

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:23.260
right, how's that R adoption going? We also do a little predictive and analysis in ML.

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:27.059
That's more on sort of the experimental phase and a lot smaller than, you know, what it

00:10:27.059 --> 00:10:32.099
is that we do a lot of. But we like to throw it in there. That way we can say we're data

00:10:32.099 --> 00:10:37.260
scientists. Again, it's all coordinated by Posit Connect, which is a really great feature.

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:44.260
So thank you, Posit. So again, Kevin Bacon, he appears again. But we started to work with

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:49.299
our VP and showing sort of what it is that we could do in terms of telling, answering

00:10:49.299 --> 00:10:53.700
that question, how is open source adoption going, as well as all the automation and everything

00:10:53.700 --> 00:11:00.700
that we put into place. And our VP loved it. Oh, man, that's incredible. But we became

